{{Use British English|date=May 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Infobox company | name = Reto-Moto ApS | logo = Reto-Moto.svg | type = [[Privately held company|Private]] | industry = [[Video game industry]] | founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1997}} | founder = <!-- or: | founders = --> | hq_location_city = [[Copenhagen]] | hq_location_country = Denmark | key_people = Jean-Marc Broyer ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]]) | products = ''[[Heroes & Generals]]'' | num_employees = 25 | num_employees_year = 2012 | website = {{URL|https://www.reto.dk/|reto.dk}} }}
'''Reto-Moto ApS''' is a Danish [[video game developer]] based in [[Copenhagen]]. Founded in 1997 and reformed in April 2008, the company is best known developing ''[[Heroes & Generals]]'' (2016).
== History == Prior to founding Reto-Moto, all founding members had been part of various [[United States]]-based [[demo group]]s, but decided to move back to [[Copenhagen]] in 1997, where they founded Reto-Moto later that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/128748/From_Hitman_to_RetoMoto_Jesper_Kyd_follows_his_own_sound.php |title=From Hitman to Reto-Moto: Jesper Kyd follows his own sound |first=Mike |last=Griffin |date= |website=gamasutra.com |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> In September 1998, Reto-Moto, at the time consisting of Jesper Vorsholt Jørgensen, Rasmus Guldberg-Kjær, Martin Munk Pollas, Karsten Lemann Hvidberg, Jacob Andersen, Janos Flösser and David Guldbrandsen, and Danish film studio [[Nordisk Film]] launched [[IO Interactive]], another developer, as a [[joint venture]].<ref name="Berlingske Business">{{cite web |url=https://www.business.dk/diverse/hitman-solgt-til-england |title=Hitman solgt til England |author= |date=4 March 2004 |website=business.dk |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Nordisk Film held a 40.3% stake in the venture, with the other 59.7% owned by Reto-Moto and its staff.<ref name="Berlingske Business" /> Due to IO Interactive's rapid success through ''[[Hitman: Codename 47]]'' in 2000, Reto-Moto was put on ice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/hitman-devs-go-solo-with-reto-moto/1100-6189099/ |title=Hitman devs go solo with Reto-Moto |first=Brendan |last=Sinclair |date=11 April 2008 |website=gamespot.com |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Eventually, all stakes in IO Interactive were sold to [[Eidos Interactive]] in March 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news040304eidosio |title=Eidos acquires Hitman developer as profits rise |author= |date= |website=eurogamer.net |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>
On 11 April 2008, four of IO Interactive's founders, namely Vorsholt Jørgensen, Pollas, Andersen and Guldbrandsen, announced that they had, together with former Eidos Interactive executive producer Neil Donnell, reformed Reto-Moto as an active developer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/52207/hitman-veterans-leave-io-form |title=Hitman Veterans Leave IO, Form Reto-Moto |author= |date= |website=Shacknews |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Guldbrandsen and Donnell became [[chief technology officer]] and [[chief executive officer]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/109173/IO_Interactive_Founders_Reform_Reto_Moto.php |title=IO Interactive Founders Reform Reto Moto |first=Mathew |last=Kumar |date= |website=gamasutra.com |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Six further former IO Interactive employees followed to Reto-Moto in December that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development/more-io-interactive-employees-join-retomoto |title=More IO Interactive employees join Reto-Moto |author= |date= |website=mcvuk.com |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> By April 2012, the company had 25 employees, of which the majority were transplants from IO Interactive.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/167663/InDepth_At_RetoMoto_AAA_veterans_speak_out_on_fascinating_culture_shift.php |title=In-Depth: At Reto-Moto, AAA veterans speak out on fascinating culture shift |first=Leigh |last=Alexander |date= |website=gamasutra.com |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>
Reto-Moto's first game, ''[[Heroes & Generals]]'', was announced on 7 October 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2011/10/10/heroes-generals-re-announced-trailered/ |title=Heroes & Generals: Re-Announced, Trailered |author= |date=10 October 2011 |website=rockpapershotgun.com |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> A temporary publishing agreement for the game was reached with [[Square Enix]] in November 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vg247.com/2012/11/07/heroes-generals-to-be-published-by-square-enix-new-shots-and-video-released/ |title=Heroes & Generals to be published by Square Enix, new shots and video released - VG247 |author= |date=7 November 2012 |website=vg247.com |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> ''Heroes & Generals'' was officially released on 23 September 2016 and has since reached 10 million registered users as of January 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/heroes-generals/heroes-generals-10-million-players-2017-content |title=MMOFPS Heroes & Generals hits 10 million players, promises more planes and vehicles |author= |date= |website=pcgamesn.com |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> On 16 August 2017, Reto-Moto hired Jean-Marc Broyer as new chief executive officer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-08-16-reto-moto-brings-on-jean-marc-broyer-as-ceo |title=Reto-Moto brings on Jean-Marc Broyer as CEO |author= |date= |website=gamesindustry.biz |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Nordisk Film announced on 6 December 2017 that they had acquired a minority stake in Reto-Moto in exchange for a {{US$|5&nbsp;million|link=yes}} investment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-12-06-nordisk-film-takes-USD5m-ownership-stake-in-heroes-and-generals-studio |title=Nordisk Film takes $5m ownership stake in Heroes & Generals studio |author= |date= |website=gamesindustry.biz |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>
